SEM results related to GQDs1 and 2 are illustrated in Fig. 2
                     . As seen from the images, the GQDs is consisted of regularly shaped particles with average size between 20 and 40nm. Fig. 3a and b show TEM of graphene quantum dots. According to the TEM images, the resulting GQDs are uniform in size ranging from 20 to 30nm in diameter (Fig. 3a) and stacking to form large particles (Fig.3b). S. Wang and co-workers report that this happens because at higher temperature most of tiny particles stack and form larger particles with inhomogeneous sizes [19]. The optical properties of the as-synthesized GQDs are investigated to figure out the possibility of using GQDs as down conversion material (Fig. 4
                     ). As seen from Fig. 4a, the ultraviolet-visible (UV/Vis) absorption spectrum of the GQDs shows two significant excitonic absorption bands at about 250 and 350nm due to π-to-π* transition of CC and n-to-π* transition of CO groups, respectively [20].Fig. 4b shows the PL spectrum of GQD1 and GQD2 which excited by 360nm and emitted photon at 450 and 520nm, respectively. Photon with this energy is favorable for DSSCs that why we used GQDs as DC. To the best of our knowledge, this is first work that uses GQDs as down conversion material in DSSCs.

We used electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS), Intensity modulated photocurrent spectroscopy (IMPS) and intensity modulated photovoltage spectroscopy (IMVS) analysis to approve that this improvement is because of down conversion of GQDs. In EIS, with increasing frequency, two semicircles are observed in the Nyquist plots (Fig. 6
                     ). The first semicircle is attributed to the charge transfer resistance between platinum counter electrode and redox couple (RCE) and the second semicircle reflecting the charge transfer resistance at the dyed-TiO2/electrolyte interface is related to charge recombination process (RCT). Results are tabled in Table 2
                     . RCE and RCT for reference cell and cell based on GQDs are close. It means that resistance and charge recombination in reference cell and cell based on GQDs are same. IMPS and IMVS can be used to calculate the respective time constants for charge collection and charge recombination at short circuit and open circuit condition in dye-sensitized solar cells [21–33]. It is expected that the loss of injected electrons via both photocurrent from external load and recombination are proportional to the electron concentration in TiO2 and the rate constants for these processes are independent of each other. The time constant for charge recombination at open circuit (τr) was obtained from IMVS. The collection (transport) time (τc) can be estimated from the equation τr=1/2πfc, where fc is the characteristic frequency maximum of the IMPS imaginary component and the charge-collection efficiency ηcc is given by the equation ηcc=1−(τc/τr). IMPS and IMVS experiments were done by a modulated AC light from 1 to 1000Hz superimposed on a relatively large bias illumination at 470nm.
